        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <div class="quotetitle">Pocky Is God wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">So if I were to batch sparge, say for a 10 gallon boil, I would split the 10 gallons into equal five gallons batches? First at 165F, put into the lauter tun, let it sit for an hour, vorloff, drain to the hot liquor tank, and then do the other 5 gallons of water to say, 173-174F and hold that for 10, then drain again to the hot liquor tank?</div><br /><br />The whole point of batch sparging is to put all the water you are going to sparge with in the mash tun at once.  If you want to elevate your mash temp to 173 for sparging just use water warm enough to do this in one batch.  So you would mash in with ~ 13 Qts and strike a mash temp of 152 to 158 (for a single step) or you could work out the details for a multi-step.  Once you've mashed for an Hour you add the rest of the liquid - you want it to reach a final rest of 173 to 175.  <br /><br />Stir the mash up while you add all this water to loosen it and get all the dissolved sugars into the solution.  recirculate a couple of quarts of wort to set the mash bed.  and then collect the mash into the brew kettle <span style="text-decoration: underline">all at once</span>. <br /><br />Personally I find this all very fiddley and prefer to fly sparge - YMMV.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
