        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <div class="quotetitle">rrrhal wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">GohanIYIan wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">Pocky Is God wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Does anyone fly sparge? <br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.northernbrewer.com/shop/deluxe-all-grain-system-10-gallon.html">http://www.northernbrewer.com/shop/delu ... allon.html</a><!-- m --><br /><br />I'm thinking I can do so with this kit, but unsure. Anyone care to help me out here?</div><br /><br />I batch sparge with essentially that exact set-up. Efficiency is typically in the 75-80% range so I've never felt any need to increase the complexity by recirculating the wort.</div><br />There are people in this world that recirculate until the wort runs clear (sparkling clear) - this is overdoing it.  You want to reduce the amount of grain husks and trub getting into the brew kettle.</div><br /><br />I just run the output through a hop bag. I used to recirculate the first quart (or so) until it was clear, but filtering with the bag is both easier and more consistent. Even after the runnings go clear, a stray grain will come out every now and then.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
