        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              So there's nothing particularly 'wrong' about not doing a mashout type temperature addition. You sacrifice the control you get from stopping the enzymatic action by bringing temps up, but this can be compensated for in a number of ways, or even ignored.<br /><br />  If you mash high (153-157), you tend towards higher proportions of large sugars/small starches in your wort. As you are collecting wort, your first runnings will have a period of time in the kettle at a lower temp (assuming you are collecting while not heating the kettle). The 138-148F temps (off the top of my head) are in the high beta-amylase activity range, which will break these higher sugars and starches into the more fermentable range, resulting in most likely a lower final gravity (within limits of the yeast, sometimes you see them give up early if your wort is too fermentable, leaving too much maltose et al.).<br /><br />If instead you do a hot water addition to bring your final runnings up first, enough of the Beta amylase will denature and your range of temps will shift up enough that most activity stops. This lets you have more control over the worts final form, at the expense of more water additions. You also get the benefit of a looser timeframe, since you don't have to hurry into the boil to avoid over-mashing.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
