          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=24299231#p24299231" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">rigeek</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=24299147#p24299147" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Kung Fu Hamster</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">After a brewing hiatus, I'm going to whip up a batch of apfelwien this weekend. BONUS: I'll finally have a chance to try out the chest freezer I got for Christmas for keeping stable fermentation temps.<br /><br />The current iteration of the recipe is:<br /><br />-5 gal 100% apple juice<br />-5 lbs turbinado sugar<br />-2 pkgs Nottingham dry yeast<br />-2 yeast nutrient<br />-1 12 oz container cranberry apple juice concentrate (priming)<br /><br />The previous batches I've made have always fermented in a water bath in a closet, so the temps have always varied. I'm going to keep this batch at about 65F this time around for a month before bottling, and give the bottles about 2 months to age before opening, meaning I'll have plenty of refreshing booze for the brutal AZ summer.<br /><br />My next version, I'm planning on reducing 6 gallons of apple juice down to 5 and dialing the turbinado back to about 3 lbs. I'd try this recipe now, but it's already approaching the &quot;too hot for brewing&quot; weather here in Phoenix.</div><br /><br />I did something very similar a couple of weeks ago.  I did a smaller batch and used the Mr Beer barrel fermenter ... their kits are shit but the little barrels are still good for small experimental batches or things like this.<br /><br />I used 2 1/2gal 100% apple cider, 1lb dextrose, and a pack of dry champagne yeast.  I sanitized the barrel and a funnel.  Poured out half of each bottle into the sanitized fermenter.  Divided up the dextrose amongst the half empty bottles, and shook the shit out of them to dissolve the dextrose.  Poured what was left into the barrel.  Pitched the yeast, sealed it up and let it sit for 3 weeks.  Was going to be all proper and bottle it and shit, but last Friday night I was sitting at my desk, looking at the barrel, and decided I wanted a taste .. so I poured some out of the spigot into my hydrometer tube, took a reading (around 0.995) and drank the sample .. then I poured a glass right out of the bucket .. and then another... and it turned into a total shitshow.  Stuff is hot and dry, like rocket fuel.. but holy shit it got the job done.  Have fun with that stuff!</div><br /><br />Thanks. This is going to be my 5th or 6th batch of apfelwien I've made thus far. I've never had much luck with champange yeast; Notty has always served me well, as long as I give it plenty to time to go through all the sugar.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
